@page "/doc/agent"
@model PetBox.Web.Pages.Doc.AgentModel
@{
	ViewData["Title"] = "Connect a coding agent — PetBox docs";
	Layout = null;
	var mcp = Model.McpUrl;
}
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en" data-theme="dark" class="h-full">
<head>
	<meta charset="utf-8" />
	<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0" />
	<title>Connect a coding agent — PetBox</title>
	<link rel="stylesheet" href="~/css/app.css" asp-append-version="true" />
</head>
<body class="min-h-full">
	<main class="prose prose-sm max-w-3xl mx-auto p-6" data-testid="doc-agent">
		<p class="text-sm opacity-60"><a href="@Routes.Doc()">← docs</a></p>
		<h1>Connect a coding agent to PetBox</h1>

		<p>
			PetBox exposes a project's <strong>task boards</strong>, <strong>memory stores</strong> and
			<strong>session plans</strong> over <strong>MCP</strong> (Model Context Protocol) — a shared,
			durable plan/notes store that survives across sessions and across different agents on a team.
			Once connected, an agent reads and writes them with the <code>tasks.*</code>, <code>memory.*</code>
			and <code>session.*</code> tools.
		</p>

		<h2>1. Get connection details</h2>
		<p>
			A workspace admin mints a project-scoped API key on the project's
			<strong>Connect agent</strong> page (under the admin gear → project → Connect agent). That page
			shows, once, the three things you need:
		</p>
		<ul>
			<li>MCP endpoint (this instance): <code data-testid="doc-agent-mcp">@mcp</code></li>
			<li>Auth header: <code>X-Api-Key: &lt;your key&gt;</code></li>
			<li>Project key: passed as <code>projectKey</code> in every tool call</li>
		</ul>

		<h2>2. Register a project-level MCP server</h2>
		<p>Add a server named <code>petbox</code> in the config file <em>your</em> agent reads:</p>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>Claude Code</strong> — <code>.mcp.json</code> (<code>mcpServers.petbox</code>, type <code>http</code>, url + headers)</li>
			<li><strong>Factory Droid</strong> — <code>.factory/mcp.json</code> (same shape)</li>
			<li><strong>opencode</strong> — <code>opencode.json</code> (<code>mcp.petbox</code>, type <code>remote</code>, url + headers, <code>enabled: true</code>)</li>
			<li><strong>omp</strong> (oh-my-pi) — its native project MCP config (HTTP url + header)</li>
			<li><strong>pi</strong> — no native MCP; bridge with <code>pi-mcp-adapter</code> against the same url + header</li>
		</ul>
		<p>Example (Claude Code <code>.mcp.json</code>):</p>
		<pre><code>{
  "mcpServers": {
    "petbox": {
      "type": "http",
      "url": "@mcp",
      "headers": { "X-Api-Key": "${PETBOX_API_KEY}" }
    }
  }
}</code></pre>

		<h2>3. Keep the key out of version control</h2>
		<p>
			Never commit the key. The config above references it as <code>${PETBOX_API_KEY}</code>, which your
			agent expands from its <strong>process environment</strong> — not from a <code>.env</code> file. Export
			it in your shell (or set it OS-wide) before launching the agent:
		</p>
		<pre><code># macOS / Linux (current shell)
export PETBOX_API_KEY=&lt;your key&gt;

# Windows (persisted for new shells)
setx PETBOX_API_KEY "&lt;your key&gt;"</code></pre>
		<p class="text-sm opacity-70">
			If your agent can't expand env vars, inline the key directly in the MCP config instead — but keep that
			config file gitignored.
		</p>

		<h2>4. The plan is a tree: Phase &gt; Wave &gt; Task</h2>
		<p>
			A task board is a <strong>1-to-3 level tree</strong>. Identify each node by its path, not a flat
			label — pass <code>phase</code> (required), optional <code>wave</code>, optional <code>task</code>
			(a task requires a wave). Each segment is lowercase <code>^[a-z][a-z0-9_-]{0,99}$</code>.
			Create a parent before (or together with) its children.
		</p>
		<p>Give every node BOTH a short <code>name</code> (one-line title) AND a <code>body</code> (the detail — what to actually do). Keep the title terse; put prose in the body.</p>
		<pre><code>tasks.upsert board="roadmap" projectKey="&lt;proj&gt;" nodes=[
  { "phase":"logging", "name":"Logging", "status":"InProgress",
    "body":"Move winston+Seq output to PetBox; read via log.query (KQL).", "priority":0 },
  { "phase":"logging", "wave":"ingest", "name":"Ingest pipeline", "status":"Pending",
    "body":"Ship CLEF lines to the ingest endpoint.", "priority":1 },
  { "phase":"logging", "wave":"ingest", "task":"endpoint", "name":"POST endpoint", "status":"Pending",
    "body":"Wire the structured-JSON POST.", "priority":2 }
]</code></pre>
		<p>
			Notes: <code>status</code> ∈ Pending|InProgress|Done|Blocked|Deferred|Cancelled. <code>priority</code>
			is a sparse ordering int (lower first). <code>version</code> is the baseline you last saw (0 = new).
			Rename/move with <code>prevPhase/prevWave/prevTask</code> (or <code>prevKey</code>). The upsert
			<strong>response already contains the fresh state</strong> (<code>added/updated/removed</code> +
			<code>currentVersion</code>) — advance your cursor and merge; you do not need to re-read the board.
		</p>

		<h2>5. Tools</h2>
		<ul>
			<li><code>tasks.board_list / board_create / board_delete</code> — named boards. A cold <code>tasks.upsert</code> auto-creates the board; <code>board_create</code> is only for setting a description up front.</li>
			<li><code>tasks.get / upsert / delta</code> — the plan tree (returns key, phase, wave, task, depth, parentKey, status, name, body, priority, version).</li>
			<li><code>memory.store_list / store_create / store_delete</code> — named memory stores (a cold <code>memory.upsert</code> auto-creates the store).</li>
			<li><code>memory.list / search / get / upsert / delta</code> — durable notes. Each entry needs a <code>type</code> (User|Feedback|Project|Reference) plus description, body, optional tags. <code>search</code> is FTS5-ranked; <code>list</code>/<code>search</code> accept an optional <code>type</code> filter.</li>
			<li><code>session.append / get / list</code> — the working-session plan blob (one per project).</li>
		</ul>

		<h2>6. Memory: tasks vs memory vs session</h2>
		<p>Three stores, pick by lifetime:</p>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>Session</strong> (<code>session.*</code>) — your <em>current</em> working plan/thinking. Ephemeral, last-write-wins. Test: “stale next week?” → session.</li>
			<li><strong>Tasks</strong> (<code>tasks.*</code>) — a <em>unit of work with a status</em> you track to Done. Test: “has a status that changes (Pending→Done)?” → task.</li>
			<li><strong>Memory</strong> (<code>memory.*</code>) — a <em>durable fact</em> that should outlive the work. Test: “will a future agent need this to avoid re-learning it?” → memory.</li>
		</ul>
		<p>
			What belongs in <strong>memory</strong>: durable facts not derivable from code/git/config — user
			preferences, project constraints, decisions-with-rationale, references. What does <em>not</em>:
			anything the repo/git already records, transient state, secrets, or actionable work (that's a task).
			Pick a <code>type</code>: <code>user</code> (who the user is), <code>feedback</code> (a correction/
			preference on how to work — include why + how to apply), <code>project</code> (a durable project
			fact/constraint — why + how to apply), <code>reference</code> (a pointer to an external resource).
		</p>
		<p>
			Maintenance: search before you write; update an existing entry rather than duplicating; delete when
			wrong (history is kept, so deletes are safe). Put prose in <code>session</code> content or a task's
			<code>body</code>; when a finished task yields a generalizable lesson, move that lesson to memory as
			<code>feedback</code> — the task's <code>commitRef</code> stays on the node.
		</p>

		<h2>7. (Optional) add a project skill</h2>
		<p>
			If your agent supports Agent Skills, drop a <code>SKILL.md</code> at the right path (Claude Code
			<code>.claude/skills/petbox/</code>; pi/omp <code>.pi/skills/</code> or <code>.agents/skills/</code>;
			Droid <code>.factory/skills/</code>; opencode <code>.opencode/skills/</code>):
		</p>
		<pre><code>---
name: petbox
description: Shared task boards, memory and session plans for this project via the PetBox MCP server (server name `petbox`). Use to record/read plans, durable notes and working-session state.
---

This project is connected to a PetBox instance over MCP (server `petbox`).
Pass projectKey "&lt;proj&gt;" in every call.

Plans are a Phase > Wave > Task tree: identify nodes by phase/wave/task (not a flat
label); give each a short `name` and a detailed `body`. A cold upsert auto-creates the
board/store. Memory entries need a `type` (User|Feedback|Project|Reference); store durable
facts there, actionable work on a task board. The upsert response is the fresh state;
advance your cursor instead of re-reading.

Tools: tasks.board_list/board_create/board_delete/get/upsert/delta,
memory.store_list/store_create/store_delete/list/search/get/upsert/delta,
session.append/get/list.</code></pre>

		<h2>8. Verify</h2>
		<p>
			Restart your MCP connection and call <code>tasks.board_list</code> with your <code>projectKey</code>.
			An empty list (not an auth error) means it works.
		</p>
	</main>
</body>
</html>
